snippet.textDisplay:
Now, I was never a huge fan/any kind of fan of it at all, just saw it when it first aired (original series) when I was younger. It was alright. Just sort of there, it's own thing, in it's own time. Probably seen every episode a dozen times over in no particular order over the years (the TV channels Dave and UK Gold are to blame mostly lol)
I was willing to give the new Christmas "Special" a fair viewing - though to be fair, with it being Christmas (sat with family and shall we say, having a democratic use of the TV remote) and as it is a favourite of my dad's, I didn't have much choice in the matter as he insisted we watch it. I just hoped for the best - but didn't expect much.
Being honest, it was embarrassingly bad. Poorly written, cheesy, leaning heavily on in-jokes and blatantly trying to cling to the actor's own collective nostalgia for it. Considering actors in this video literally saw it as a bit of a one-off, or even a holiday to film it, that is about all we need to know.

However, on top of that is simply how it was vacuous, lowest common denominator pandering, clawing, boring, self-indulgent in it's own hype and generally a really dull waste of time. Nowhere near living up to the hype. It was just sort of going through the motions of recreating Gavin & Stacey - with stilted dialogue, painfully unfunny attempts at comedy and moments where the farce it really was just distracted me right out of the scene. Was Nessa buying an individual bathroom tap for everyone really meant to be funny? It was just a low end attempt at non sequitur humour. At least stay in your lane G&S -.-' leave surrealist comedy to the experts (like Reeves and Mortimer for a fair example)
Not only were aspects like that, so dumb they broke any immersion I may have had, but they just didn't work regardless of that. I'd sometimes turn a blind eye to it if the desired effect - you know, making people laugh? - worked even if it made zero sense.

For instance, many story-lines in Phoenix Nights by Peter Kay, et al, are far-fetched at points though generally work anyway. Like G&S, Phoenix Nights is fictional, though grounded in some sort of realism, anchored keenly in the real world. Barry Island is real; so are Bolton and Chorley. The settings for both shows are keenly real, epitomes of Wales for G&S or North West England in the case of Phoenix Nights.
Obviously characters, events and plot lines, are fictional. But they are anchored, inextricably, in their real world settings; having a sort of meta significance on-screen (especially, of course, to those regions they come from)
Both have farcical, far-fetched aspects. Most can be funny. But not the G&S 2019 Christmas "Special".
e.g. a drunk horse literally mounts and shags a bucking bronco machine in a function room of the Phoenix Club, and the effect is achieved mostly off-screen with squeaky noises - obviously a horse didn't really do that lol) It's clearly just for a laugh - a pissed horse, shitting all over the place and humping a bucking bronco machine on a Wild West themed night (that, being the tenuous yet passable link which excused writing in a scene where a horse helps itself to the beer pumps in an unused room -.-)
Yes, obviously it's mental - but it's funny!
G&S 2019 Christmas "Special" was so caught up in it's own hype and nostalgia, it forgot to be truly funny. Anyone really, seriously thinking this dross was ''funny'' either have questionable taste in comedy or something worse lol Banality at it's finest.
Naturally, all the lovies who think it is ''classic British comedy'' (which has really been gone for a long time now, due to political bias at the beeb - ostracising comedians whom do not fit their criteria; i.e. assimilate or be banished etc) will shower it with praise and call it great telly. Well, it isn't. It is utterly vapid, not even funny by accident.

Genuinely, I was willing to give it a chance, but it was simply low quality. No getting round it. Oh well.
Besides the opinion fact that James Corden is a talent-less boob with all the charm of a pile of rancid cat shit, who somehow parlayed his role in the original Gavin & Stacey series into a full-blown career in Hollywood ''earning'' multi-millions (Corden is so annoying that his very voice puts me off anything he is in - let alone something he is literally screaming and shouting in sigh -.-' dear Lord he is one irritating, unfunny, grasping opportunist)
His presence in it alone (with Smithy having apparently more dialogue than Gavin?), mugging the camera in every scene, is normally enough to make me turn the channel over.
5 minutes in, I realised the level it was going to cruise along at, aping on it's own hype and nostalgia, and I wanted to watch something better.
Only reason I saw it all in one go was because of it being Christmas and kinda forced to sit through it (one family member cleverly dodged it by going to the kitchen half way through, not coming back :') didn't blame them)
I was so bored half way in I barely paid attention, preferring to read a book.
Nobody laughed at anything - on wait, no, there was a little laughter regarding the scene where the parents of G&S and Pam's friends smoke weed and prat about...but I wasn't laughing. I just thought it was weird and lazily written.
IT'S FUNNY COS THEY ARE OLD AND GETTING HIGH HAHA HAHA LAUGH PEASANTS LAUGH HAHA
and I'm just like no
What a load of old horse shite.

Conclusion and rating:
Do not watch, absolute rubbish. Seen funnier adverts and that is setting the bar extremely low.
2/10
James Corden personally responsible for it not being 4/10
...or in other words;
"STEP INTO DOGSHIT, STEP INTO DOGSHIT" - sung/shouted by James Corden, as he mugs the camera, as he admires his own farts face (before he goes to do some more screaming in ''Cats''; another abomination)
...or in other words;
"America, please keep him" =.='

P.S - It is obvious the BBC are angling this to test the waters for a potential Season 4 of G&S. Let's not be gullible enough to believe this video's claims they aren't interested in further production. It's show biz, of course it would have been discussed lol :') that they try to act like it hasn't been is pretty unbelievable.
Nice little money spinner for them isn't it? Well, no thanks.

Nowhere near living up to the hype. It was just sort of going through the motions of recreating Gavin & Stacey - with stilted dialogue, painfully unfunny attempts at comedy and moments where the farce it really was just distracted me right out of the scene. Was Nessa buying an individual bathroom tap for everyone really meant to be funny? It was just a low end attempt at non sequitur humour. At least stay in your lane G&S -.-' leave surrealist comedy to the experts (like Reeves and Mortimer for a fair example)
Not only were aspects like that, so dumb they broke any immersion I may have had, but they just didn't work regardless of that. I'd sometimes turn a blind eye to it if the desired effect - you know, making people laugh? - worked even if it made zero sense.

 For instance, many story-lines in Phoenix Nights by Peter Kay, et al, are far-fetched at points though generally _work_ anyway. Like G&S, Phoenix Nights is fictional, though grounded in some sort of realism, anchored keenly in the real world. Barry Island is real; so are Bolton and Chorley. The settings for both shows are keenly real, epitomes of Wales for G&S or North West England in the case of Phoenix Nights. 
Obviously characters, events and plot lines, are fictional. But they are anchored, inextricably, in their real world settings; having a sort of meta significance on-screen (especially, of course, to those regions they come from)
Both have farcical, far-fetched aspects. Most can be funny. But not the G&S 2019 Christmas "Special".
e.g. a drunk horse literally mounts and shags a bucking bronco machine in a function room of the Phoenix Club, and the effect is achieved mostly off-screen with squeaky noises - obviously a horse didn't really do that lol) It's clearly just for a laugh - a pissed horse, shitting all over the place and humping a bucking bronco machine on a Wild West themed night (that, being the tenuous yet passable link which excused writing in a scene where a horse helps itself to the beer pumps in an unused room -.-)
Yes, obviously it's mental - but it's funny! 
G&S 2019 Christmas "Special" was so caught up in it's own hype and nostalgia, it forgot to be truly funny. Anyone really, seriously thinking this dross was ''funny'' either have questionable taste in comedy or something worse lol Banality at it's finest. 
Naturally, all the lovies who think it is ''classic British comedy'' (which has really been gone for a long time now, due to political bias at the beeb - ostracising comedians whom do not fit their criteria; i.e. assimilate or be banished etc) will shower it with praise and call it great telly. Well, it isn't. It is utterly vapid, not even funny by accident.

Genuinely, I was willing to give it a chance, but it was simply low quality. No getting round it. Oh well.
Besides the -opinion- fact that James Corden is a talent-less boob with all the charm of a pile of rancid cat shit, who somehow parlayed his role in the original Gavin & Stacey series into a full-blown career in Hollywood ''earning'' multi-millions (Corden is so annoying that his very voice puts me off anything he is in - let alone something he is _literally screaming and shouting in_ sigh -.-' dear Lord he is one irritating, unfunny, grasping opportunist) 
His presence in it alone (with Smithy having apparently more dialogue than Gavin?), mugging the camera in every scene, is normally enough to make me turn the channel over.
5 minutes in, I realised the level it was going to cruise along at, aping on it's own hype and nostalgia, and I wanted to watch something better.
Only reason I saw it all in one go was because of it being Christmas and kinda forced to sit through it (one family member cleverly dodged it by going to the kitchen half way through, not coming back :') didn't blame them)
I was so bored half way in I barely paid attention, preferring to read a book.
Nobody laughed at anything - on wait, no, there was a little laughter regarding the scene where the parents of G&S and Pam's friends smoke weed and prat about...but I wasn't laughing. I just thought it was weird and lazily written.
_IT'S FUNNY COS THEY ARE OLD AND GETTING HIGH HAHA HAHA LAUGH PEASANTS LAUGH HAHA_
and I'm just like *no*
What a load of old horse shite.

_Conclusion_ and rating:
Do not watch, absolute rubbish. Seen funnier adverts and that is setting the bar extremely low.
2/10
*James Corden personally responsible for it not being 4/10*
...or in other words;
"STEP INTO DOGSHIT, STEP INTO DOGSHIT" - sung/shouted by James Corden, as he mugs the camera, as he admires his own -farts- face (before he goes to do some more screaming in ''Cats''; another abomination)
...or in other words;
"America, please keep him"  =.='

P.S - It is obvious the BBC are angling this to test the waters for a potential Season 4 of G&S. Let's not be gullible enough to believe this video's claims they aren't interested in further production. It's show biz, of course it would have been discussed lol :') that they try to act like it hasn't been is pretty unbelievable.
Nice little money spinner for them isn't it? Well, no thanks.
